this movie did NOT open at #1. I included not one but TWO reputable sources that PROVE that this movie opened at #2. here is the chart: http://www.ew.com/ew/chart/movie/0,6115,_1__,00.html
internet phenomena deserves its own sentence. the poor box office doesn't diminish the impact of the movie's appeal on the internet. it can still be a web phenomena even if the movie didn't do well

I like the new addition to the Slither page, "more neutral sounding."
grammar fixes. included the word HOWEVER to indicate that, despite the poor box office performance, Slither was well received by critics., etc.

included EW must list for Apr. Couldn't find anything in print suggesting that critics think this is the best horror film in the last 5 years. But it is A FACT that Slither did appear #1 on this list.
moved reception stuff to the appropriate category. also removed subjective POV stuff. moved novel link to appropriate category
removed libel. will report abuse. perform IP check if you don't believe who I am. you are wrong in your accusation Sensorium.

included Lloyd Kaufman with David Cronenberg in trivia section as an influence on Gunn. After all, Gunn made Tromeo and Juliet with Kaufman
deleted POV stuff and opinion stuff, "weasel words" that praise James Gunn. This isn't a celebrity fanpage for James Gunn. Clearly violates wiki standards.
Replaced 84%  Rottentomatoes.com statement with something more neutral. this isn't a James Gunn fanpage... Please STOP trying to turn this into a promotional page. Stick to the FACTS or don't post.
replaced David Cronenberg with Lloyd Kaufman. James Gunn's movies (Scooby Doo, Dawn of the Dead, The Specials) don't resemble Cronenberg movies. Cronenberg DOESN'T make comedies.
removed convoluted and confusing, opinionated statement about slither's critical reaction. statement calls Slither UNIQUE and suggests it was groundbreaking WITHOUT providing sources.
emoved POV about 84% high rating. Slither was not a revolutionary horror film. it was not ground breaking. Slither didn't have a cultural impact. therefore, it is not worth mentioning
removed POV about 84% high rating. Slither was not a revolutionary horror film. it was not ground breaking. Slither didn't have a cultural impact. therefore, it is not worth mentioning.
removed James Gunn picture. Picture is copywrite protected. violates wiki standard.
Removed 84% rottentomatoes.com rating since it is misleading. For instance, the descent has 83% over at Rottentomatoes.com. In other words, Slither is NOT unique in its high score. form of "spinning"
picture violate wiki policy. picture is copywritten protected. removed picture
removed POV and OPINION stuff from page. Uses "weasel words" which are violation of Wiki policy.
REMOVED FALSE STATMENT/LIE from page. Blair Witch Project ALSO has 84% rating at Rottentomatoes.com. so statement isn't true. WILL REPORT ABUSE
84% rating is not notable. plus statement is not true. other horror films on "Rotten tomatoes" has received
removed MORE subjective content. you did not list sources showing HIGH PRAISE from Hooper, Roth, Zombie, Landis. Pure speculation. violates wiki standards.
deleted POV stuff. we don't need to remind the reader of HOW HIGH the rotten tomatoe rating is. not necessary. readers can draw there own conclusions. this movie was not a cultural phenomena.
TRIVIA change: "Shiver" reference confusing. created its own section for it.
COSTS UPDATE: I included BOX OFFICE MOJO and HOLLYWOOD REPORTER as sources for budget. they don't contradict. one has production costs. the other has marketing. I will create 2 sections for both.
REMOVED ALL SUBJECTIVE/OPINION STATEMENTS. "best horror film?" come on. that's opinion. I addressed concerns in TALK PAGE. kept some revisions, reverted others. Will report abuse if happens again.
changes were TOO subjective and TOO promotional. DO NOT turn WIKI into a promotional site. please continue discussion in talk section BEFORE you vandalize this page again!
removed picture. doesn't have copywrite tag. read wiki rules.
/* Removed recently inserted section from article */
please don't intentionally mislead readers by leaving out marketing costs. $29.5 million is the total budget for this film. Sources have been provided and they check out. Will report continued abuse
WAY TOO subjective, period. best horror film in 10 years? please provide link. too subjective/opinionated. don't mix critical acclaim with box office topic. typical "red-herring." revert to original.
needs to be more "neutral." words like critically acclaimed and extremely received are subjective. please don't make Wiki into corporate spin for celebrites. violates wiki rules. will revert back.
see talk for changes before you edit it this
this is more neutral sounding. I have backed this assertion up with a source that itself was also backed up by several sources (i.e. Slither's producer, also filmmaker Eli Roth, etc.)

fixed grammar... divided critical response and public response in their own categories
made sure to seperate subject of financial and critical response so there would be no confusion. one doesn't have anything to do with the other.
don't lump the reaction of critics in a sentence WITH the financial business of the film. these are BOTH different subjects and one topic shouldn't distract from the reality of the other.
while box office bomb is too strong a word, the word 'failure' is not. industry analysts clearly regard this movie as a box office 'failure'. I've backed this up with sources
removed the word "largely" since it's too subjective/opinionated and substituted with it "many". some major critics, like Ebert and Roeper, didn't like it. "largely" distorts this. also fixed grammar

david cronenberg doesn't make horror comedies. he also doesn't believe in alien life. clearly David Cronenberg can't be considered a bonefide inspiration for this film. But Lloyd Kaufman certainly is.
fixed run off sentence, strange grammar. etc.
edited out the praise from other directors since there are no sources backing this up. please post links to John Landis or others saying "this is the best horror movie they have seen in years."
more balanced description of box office. it is agreed, even by the president of the company that made SOAP said that the opening weekend was "disappointing"

this movie WAS NOT a hit. I backed up this RECEPTION section with sources. don't delete this just because you are a fan of the film. and the movie is NOT #1 (check boxofficemojo.com if you doubt this)
see reason below in my edit below...
several inaccuracies. film did not open at #1. it opened at #2. film is also considered by industry to be financial disappointment. backed up this analysis with WIKI approved sources
"Box office bomb" is a loaded term. While it was a failure - it was no town and country or Cutthroat Island. Reduce wikilinking to the film.
